09225nam a22011775i 9783868598001DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97838685980017 a10.1515/97838685980012doi  a(DE-B1597)627068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aNA2500 7aARC0060002bisacsh04a720223/eng/20220929  aMS 18102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123615:00aLifelines :bPolitics, ethics, and the affective economy of inhabiting /ced. by Camillo Boano, Cristina Bianchetti. 1aBerlin : bJOVIS Verlag GmbH, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tLifelines: the stakes of life in the project -- tCartographies of protection -- tPart 1. Promise and failure of infrastructures -- tIntroduction -- tBroken distribution logistics inspire a shorter ecological supply chain -- tCoca, cattle, and cities: fluid lifelines in the frontier of Caquetá, Colombia -- tEcological lifelines -- tProduction lifelines: Suzhou’s resistive lifelines and mutual support -- tBeyond the transport infrastructure: the paradigm of accessibility -- tPublic Works’ Housing Monitor: digital lifelines for urban advocacy in Lebanon -- tCulture and heritage infrastructure as ‘lifelines’ in east London -- tPart 2. Spaces of lifelines and lifelines of spaces -- tIntroduction -- tBodily knowledges and spatial production practices in the Ecuadorian Amazon: a decolonial analysis -- tMisappropriation and occupation: lifelines and artistic practices for the city of Beirut -- tAutonomous spaces in Berlin: cynical resistance tactics in the neoliberal city -- tTaranto: a system of necrotized spaces protecting life -- tFracture and resistance lines of modern designed spatial infrastructures -- tContradictions in housing: lifelines in Santiago de Chile -- tPart 3. The dark side of protection -- tIntroduction -- tBorgo Mezzanone: vicious circles that keep informality together -- tThe ambivalent nature of productive lifelines: values without waste and landscape without inhabitation -- tThe Beik infrastructure of loyalists: Sawfar’s fragmented lifelines -- tViral politics: protection lifelines granting differentiated conditions of vulnerability during the Covid-19 outbreak in Brescia, Italy -- tInhabiting Tell Serhoun: holding places operated to confront the uninhabitable -- tPart 4. Towards a permanent seminar -- tThe afterlife of Lifelines -- tEditors’ and authors’ biographies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDurch das Aufeinandertreffen von Gesundheits- und Klimakrise ist ein Rückgriff auf bislang bewährte Forschungsansätze im Bereich des Wohnens nicht mehr zielführend. Wie prägen die geografischen und politischen Entwicklungen das heutige Wohnen?Lifelines ist eine Gemeinschaftsforschungsarbeit zu Räumen, in denen sich Lebensformen vermischen, durchdringen und verflechten – und zwar in ständigem Widerstand gegen die Mechanismen einer techno-kapitalistischen Gegenwart, die soziale und ökologische Unsicherheiten nicht nur abbilden, sondern auch erzeugen und nutzen. Die Autor*innen beleuchten die Herausforderungen, die sich dem heutigen Entwerfen stellen, und untersuchen die Rolle, die dem Entwerfen in prekären Räumen zukommt. Das Buch versammelt empirische Untersuchungen aus Italien, Ecuador, den USA, dem Libanon, Deutschland und Großbritannien.  aIn the face of the radical convergence of a health crisis and an ecological crisis, it is not possible to return to the investigative trajectories on inhabitation and dwelling that yielded good results in the past. What is it that now defines inhabitation within the plurality of conditions, geographies, and politics that connote it? Lifelines is a work of collective research on the spaces where life intertwines, mingles, and twists in constant resistance to the mechanisms that capture, exploit, and create the social and environmental precariousness that characterizes the violent techno-capitalist present.The book investigates the roles and challenges of design in uncertain spaces and brings together empirical explorations from Italy, Ecuador, the US, Lebanon, Germany, and the UK.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aArchitecture. 4aArchitektur. 4aGemeinschaftsforschungsarbeit. 4aGesundheitskrise. 4aKlimakrise. 4aempirisch. 4aprekäre Räume. 4asozial. 4atechno-kapitalistisch. 4averflechten. 4aökologisch. 7aARCHITECTURE / Individual Architects & Firms / General.2bisacsh1 aAbdallah, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlioni, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBekdache, Nadine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBello, Elisabetta M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBianchetti, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBianchetti, Cristina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoano, Camillo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoano, Camillo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampli, Antonio di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavallaro, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCusanno, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDabaj, Joana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDianin, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoglio, Federica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel